The saying “There’s something about the outside of a horse that is good for the inside of a man” has been attributed to many famous people, from Socrates to Winston Churchill to Mark Twain. Actually, all these people might well have uttered the words – and why not? Horses are beguiling, and simply looking at them can lift the spirit. It’s something about their inner stillness; wildness allied to fragile trust. This is poignant because humans, in particular, often don’t warrant such trust from animals. Someone else described horses as “visiting gods”, which rings true as one leans on a...